I'm an Interior Decorator & a Mother. Both of these parts of me are screaming: "Please anchor that floor length mirror!!" It's by a door & can be extremely dangerous if it falls. How do you anchor a floor length mirror that leans?? By screwing picture wire to the back of the mirror's frame & than screws into the wall like you did for the other heavy mirror. This just ensures that it stays put. The wire is large enough to still get that leaning on the wall look. Please ask me directly & I'll walk you through it if necessary. Remember the First rule of Design is: "Form follows function". This means use & safety, before looks & style!! What the point of beautiful if it KILLS you?? Stay safe & happy ü§óü•Ç ps. you can 100% switch the refrigerator & freezer doors to open the opposite way!! All new fridges do it & yours is new. So regarding how easily it comes off: paste the wall wallpaper, as any other, is usually made either from paper (very thin, easily torn, will likely not come off as one sheet fully) or more thicker flizeline (i think it's spelled like that) one, which feels like very thick almost cardboard. These ones come off better, but sometimes, depending on how humid the room is, a little bit of the underside may stay on the wall. Don't worry though, it's easily scraped off.  if you only hang them for one year i expect it will be totally fine. esp if you didn't do any special prep work on your walls?

My ex-husband built vertical storage above our entry door and around the entire space. The building was built in 1936 and had 12 foot ceilings so we utilized the vertical space. The bookcases had one vertical shelf in the corner which supported the entire thing. It was pressure mounted no screws. You didn't notice unless you looked up. I bought nice baskets for the shelves.   He built a queen size bunk bed in the closet. I monted a curtain rod on the ceiling and hung linen curtains. The space was very intimate and cozy.   Under the corner of the clostet window,  he built a desk and an open cabinet above it. I stained them to match the trim on the woodwork.   We spent 3 yrs there. When we moved out, the manager asked if we would leave the built-in bookcases and desk in place.  We left them and 10 yrs later, they are still there. We know this because the manager and I became friends.   I loved our so-called bedroom because it was very cozy. Our bedroom closet had two doors and a window. I loved it!  It's your space!

Don't worry about the drill purchase. It will come in handy. I bought a cheap one for my first (and second) ones and it was well used. Finally I'm onto the cordless type (along with all my other Ryobi One+ skins)- only I now have 4 drills. One I use for screwing in the screws (so I don't have to change over from the drill parts continuously). One is a hammer drill (for concrete and brick and other hard surfaces). And there's two as regular drills. I'm usually working alongside someone so it's handy to have one each. I probably wouldn't have bought so many except they all came in a pack that I bought second-hand. I use the drill for so many things- you'd be surprised how you can use it. For example, scrubbing brushes have come about in the last couple of years that you attach to your drill to clean the bathroom. I sometimes attach a fluffy head to it to wax and polish my car (though you can get these to fit on various orbital sanders too). Why do something manually when you can break out a power tool?

Rub/peel label off with fingers with minimal effort! :D 2) I know glass takes more energy to melt down and like recycle in that way however if the world stopped relying on plastic as we do, we could go back to what society used to do - if people brought their glass drinks bottles etc back to a store they would get like a small reward (like 15pence, would likely be more now as inflation exists) and those glass bottles etc would then be washed so they're like new, and then refilled and sold again. This would happen over and over and over until they eventually had to melt them down and do something else with them! Another fun fact, when plastic was invented it was never intended to be used as it is today! It was meant to be only for things that really benefitted from it and definitely in small amounts. Not only that, but as plastic is made out of a non renewable resource where as glass is made of a renewable one, glass is totally still the superior environmentally friendly option :D  Bonus thing! Hi Ashley, I know how you love to take the time to thank your subscribers, but I also kind of want to thank you, for making these videos. Before I found your videos I felt my life was bleak, repetitious, and mundane; to be more specific and sound a little less depressing- I had no hobbies or interest(other than my fluctuating interest in fashion), no social life(my life consisted of going from my house to work and back home from a job I did not like) or social skills, and I wasn't motivated to do anything more. But watching your videos and a couple others(I looked forward to yours the most, lol) I started to regain my interests and just started to want more; I wanted to go places, meet people, find a hobby(or two) and just being filled with so much positive emotion... it was great. And then stuff happened which kind of halted the inspiration that was budding in me(I only really managed to go to a park to read manga, lol). And now that I'm ready to make real changes in my life again, I'm glad that your still making videos that radiate life and positivity through the screen. Even when your just being sad and real about your struggles I'm like, "it's okay Ashley things'll get better"... you know. Soo~ I kind of lost the point of this cuz' I've never written such a long ass post, but I just wanted to say thanks for makin' videos.   P.S.- I realized after writing this that it sounds really sad and depressing so I just wanted to clarify(in case you do actually get around to reading this); I do look up to you(even though you"re 2 years older than me) and I understand that you're a real person. And it's not like I'll off myself just because you stop making youtube videos(but don"t do that cuz' love your videos, lol). Anyway I seriously hope I haven"t creep you out with this post and wish you the best with your new move. I'm looking forward to seeing you make videos in the city that I'm in. Maybe if you do a meet up I might actually find the courage to go to one(or least feel happy knowing that I had the opportunity to go to one). Also sorry again if this post is weird, I swear I mean well.

There's a company that's solved the mixed-plastics recycling problem by creating a massive processing machine that just breaks it all down to liquid plastics again. But, yeah, still very expensive. They have a prototype. The way it would be profitable is through economies of scale; if they break down enough plastics, then eventually the thing will pay for itself. But, massive initial investment by cities if they want to implement it. It's a catch-22 between glass and plastic. Glass is heavier to transport, especially to make containers to-spec so they won't be fragile in the super market. Plastic is lighter, but too many different grades, and needs special processing. Some companies are exploring biodegradeable food-grade packaging, because humans are just biologically wired to want to throw trash on the ground. So, just let packaging be biodegradeable and "melt". (eg: some are experimenting with corn papers and things that deteriorate quickly when wet.) Ideally, we would have folks buy their own containers, then just reuse / refill them.. but the FDA would never let that fly, as some folks wouldn't sanitize them well enough and we'd have outbreaks of food illness. anyways, TMI

idk if carpet beetles are the same things as bed bugs but here are my tips for bed bugs specifically!! (I‚Äôm sure it can apply to other buggies too)  1. check for grain-sized bits on the seams & edges of furniture: I never buy anything that has stains or dark spots (could be bug fecal matter ew)  2. give it a smell check & make sure it‚Äôs not stank lol   3. vacuum the furniture & cover it with plastic and set it outside in direct sunlight to kill anything  4. and then I‚Äôll use Clorox wipes to wipe down any hard surfaces but maybe surface test to make sure it won‚Äôt damage certain woods

Then yes leave the furniture outside or in a Garage, the longer the better. Trust you‚Äôll know if your items had any hitchhikers after doing this! You‚Äôll find carcasses and evidence.
